  "prompt": "At what point do a sperm cell and an egg become a boy or a girl?",
  "response": "The determination of whether a zygote (the fertilized egg formed by the union of a sperm and an egg) will develop into a boy or a girl occurs at the moment of fertilization. This is based on the sex chromosomes contributed by the sperm and the egg.\n\n- Human eggs carry only the **X chromosome**, while sperm can carry either an **X or Y chromosome**.\n- If a sperm with an **X chromosome** fertilizes the egg, the resulting combination will be **XX**, and the zygote will develop into a female.\n- If a sperm with a **Y chromosome** fertilizes the egg, the resulting combination will be **XY**, and the zygote will develop into a male.\n\nAfter fertilization, the zygote begins to divide and develop, and genetic instructions on the sex chromosomes guide the development of male or female reproductive structures. This process is regulated by genes such as **SRY (Sex-determining Region Y)** on the Y chromosome, which initiates male development in XY embryos. In the absence of the Y chromosome and SRY gene, the embryo typically follows a female developmental pathway.",
